[0m[49m[39m  196, 198[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  197, 199[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  198, 200[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  199, 201[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  200, 202[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  201, 203[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend Medical, Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Lambda, Amazon Location Service |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 202     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend:DetectEntities`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `geo:SearchPlaceIndexForText` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend:DetectEntities`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `geo:SearchPlaceIndexForText`. Scope all permissions to specific resource ARNs in production (for example, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint` scoped to `arn:aws:sagemaker:REGION:ACCOUNT:endpoint/sdoh-ner-model`). |
[0m[49m[39m  203, 205[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | Required. Clinical notes and SDOH data are PHI. All services must be covered under your AWS BAA. |
[0m[49m[39m  204, 206[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets. DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default). SageMaker: KMS-encrypted training data, model artifacts, and endpoint traffic. All transit over TLS. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 205     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker endpoints and Glue jobs in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, Comprehend Medical, and CloudWatch Logs. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker endpoints and Glue jobs in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, Comprehend Medical, Location Service, and CloudWatch Logs. |
[0m[49m[39m  206, 208[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls. SDOH data access must be auditable. |
[0m[49m[39m  207, 209[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic clinical notes with SDOH mentions. MIMIC-III/IV contains social history sections. CDC SVI data is publicly available. Never use real patient notes in development. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 208     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend Medical: ~$0.01 per 100 characters. SageMaker endpoint: ~$0.05/hour (ml.m5.large). Glue: ~$0.44/DPU-hour. Per-patient total depends on note volume; estimate $0.15-$0.40 per patient for initial phenotyping. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend Medical: ~$0.01 per 100 characters. SageMaker endpoint: ~$0.05/hour (ml.m5.large). Glue: ~$0.44/DPU-hour. Per-patient total depends on note volume; estimate $0.15-$0.40 per patient for initial phenotyping. Cross-AZ data transfer costs apply for batch processing and should be factored into per-patient estimates for large populations. |
[0m[49m[39m  209, 211[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  210, 212[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  211, 213[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  212, 214[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  213, 215[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  214, 216[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | Base NLP extraction of medical and social entities from clinical notes |
[0m[49m[39m  215, 217[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts fine-tuned SDOH NER model; runs clustering processing jobs; serves real-time phenotype assignment |
[0m[49m[39m  216, 218[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake for notes, extractions, features, and results |
[0m[49m[39m  217, 219[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL for combining NLP output, screening data, and community indicators into feature matrix |
[0m[49m[39m  218, 220[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Real-time phenotype lookup by patient ID |
[0m[49m[39m  219, 221[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Event-driven orchestration of extraction pipeline |
[0m[49m[39m  220, 222[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Location Service** | Geocoding patient addresses to census tracts |
[0m[49m[39m  221, 223[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing stores |
[0m[49m[39m  222, 224[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Pipeline monitoring, extraction quality metrics, drift detection |
[0m[49m[39m  223, 225[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  224, 226[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  225, 227[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  226, 228[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  227, 229[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  228, 230[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: NLP extraction from clinical notes.** When new clinical notes arrive in the data lake, the system extracts SDOH-relevant mentions. This is a two-pass approach: first, Amazon Comprehend Medical identifies general medical entities and social history mentions. Second, a fine-tuned SDOH-specific model (hosted on SageMaker) performs targeted extraction for the six core SDOH domains. The two-pass approach matters because Comprehend Medical catches broad patterns efficiently, while the specialized model handles the indirect, nuanced language of social determinants that general models miss. Skip this step and you're limited to the 20-40% of patients who completed structured screening tools.
[0m[49m[39m  229, 231[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  230, 232[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  231, 233[0m:[39m[49m SDOH_DOMAINS = ["housing", "food", "transportation", "financial", "social_isolation", "safety"]
[0m[49m[39m  232, 234[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  233, 235[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_sdoh_from_note(note_text, patient_id, encounter_date):
[0m[49m[39m  234, 236[0m:[39m[49m     // Pass 1: Use managed NLP service for broad entity detection.
[0m[49m[39m  235, 237[0m:[39m[49m     // This catches explicit mentions like "homeless" or "food stamps"
[0m[49m[39m  236, 238[0m:[39m[49m     // and provides medical context (diagnoses, medications) that helps
[0m[49m[39m  237, 239[0m:[39m[49m     // disambiguate social mentions.
[0m[49m[39m  238, 240[0m:[39m[49m     medical_entities = call ComprehendMedical.DetectEntities(Text = note_text)
[0m[49m[39m  239, 241[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  240, 242[0m:[39m[49m     // Filter to social-history-relevant entities.
[0m[49m[39m  241, 243[0m:[39m[49m     // Comprehend Medical categorizes entities; we want the ones tagged
[0m[49m[39m  242, 244[0m:[39m[49m     // as social history, personal attributes, or behavioral factors.
[0m[49m[39m  243, 245[0m:[39m[49m     social_mentions = filter medical_entities where Category in
[0m[49m[39m  244, 246[0m:[39m[49m         ["SOCIAL_DETERMINANT", "BEHAVIORAL_ENVIRONMENTAL_SOCIAL"]
[0m[49m[39m  245, 247[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  246, 248[0m:[39m[49m     // Pass 2: Use fine-tuned SDOH NER model for nuanced extraction.
[0m[49m[39m  247, 249[0m:[39m[49m     // This model was trained specifically on clinical text annotated
[0m[49m[39m  248, 250[0m:[39m[49m     // for SDOH mentions, including indirect language like
[0m[49m[39m  249, 251[0m:[39m[49m     // "patient reports skipping meals to pay rent."
[0m[49m[39m  250, 252[0m:[39m[49m     sdoh_extractions = call SageMaker.InvokeEndpoint(
[0m[49m[39m  251, 253[0m:[39m[49m         EndpointName = "sdoh-ner-model",
[0m[49m[39m  252, 254[0m:[39m[49m         Body = note_text
[0m[49m[39m  253, 255[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  254, 256[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  255, 257[0m:[39m[49m     // Merge results from both passes, deduplicating overlapping spans.
[0m[49m[39m  256, 258[0m:[39m[49m     // Each extraction includes: domain, text_span, assertion (affirmed/negated),
[0m[49m[39m  257, 259[0m:[39m[49m     // confidence score, and character offsets in the original note.
[0m[49m[39m  258, 260[0m:[39m[49m     merged = deduplicate_and_merge(social_mentions, sdoh_extractions)
[0m[49m[39m  259, 261[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  260, 262[0m:[39m[49m     // Classify assertion status for each mention.
[0m[49m[39m  261, 263[0m:[39m[49m     // "Patient denies food insecurity" is NEGATED.
[0m[49m[39m  262, 264[0m:[39m[49m     // "Patient reports difficulty affording food" is AFFIRMED.
[0m[49m[39m  263, 265[0m:[39m[49m     // "If patient loses housing" is HYPOTHETICAL.
[0m[49m[39m  264, 266[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each mention in merged:
[0m[49m[39m  265, 267[0m:[39m[49m         mention.assertion = classify_assertion(mention.text_span, note_text)
[0m[49m[39m  266, 268[0m:[39m[49m         mention.domain = map_to_sdoh_domain(mention, SDOH_DOMAINS)
[0m[49m[39m  267, 269[0m:[39m[49m         mention.patient_id = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  268, 270[0m:[39m[49m         mention.encounter_date = encounter_date
[0m[49m[39m  269, 271[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  270, 272[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN merged
[0m[49m[39m  271, 273[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  272, 274[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  273, 275[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Feature assembly.** This step combines three data sources into a single patient feature vector: NLP extractions from notes, structured screening responses, and community-level indicators linked via geocoding. The challenge is handling missingness honestly. A patient with no NLP mentions might have no social needs, or might simply have sparse documentation. A patient with no screening data wasn't necessarily screened negative; they may never have been asked. The feature vector must encode these distinctions because they affect clustering behavior. Treating "never screened" as "no needs" would systematically undercount SDOH burden in populations with less documentation.
[0m[49m[39m  274, 276[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S1 (HIGH). Add guidance on geocoding PHI: recommend geocoding at zip+4 level (not full street address) when census-tract precision suffices for ADI/SVI lookup; call Location Service via VPC endpoint; cache geocode results in the feature store to avoid repeated address transmission; include geocoding calls in application-level audit logging. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  275, 279[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  276, 280[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION assemble_patient_features(patient_id, lookback_months = 24):
[0m[49m[39m  277, 281[0m:[39m[49m     features = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  278, 282[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  279, 283[0m:[39m[49m     // --- NLP-derived features ---
[0m[49m[39m  280, 284[0m:[39m[49m     // Pull all SDOH extractions for this patient within the lookback window.
[0m[49m[39m  281, 285[0m:[39m[49m     extractions = query S3 for sdoh-extractions where
[0m[49m[39m  282, 286[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id = patient_id AND
[0m[49m[39m  283, 287[0m:[39m[49m         encounter_date >= (today - lookback_months)
[0m[49m[39m  284, 288[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  285, 289[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each domain in SDOH_DOMAINS:
[0m[49m[39m  286, 290[0m:[39m[49m         domain_mentions = filter extractions where domain = domain AND assertion = "AFFIRMED"
[0m[49m[39m  287, 291[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  288, 292[0m:[39m[49m         // Binary: was this domain ever mentioned as present?
[0m[49m[39m  289, 293[0m:[39m[49m         features[domain + "_present"] = (count of domain_mentions > 0)
[0m[49m[39m  290, 294[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  291, 295[0m:[39m[49m         // Frequency: how often was it mentioned? More mentions suggest persistence.
[0m[49m[39m  292, 296[0m:[39m[49m         features[domain + "_mention_count"] = count of domain_mentions
[0m[49m[39m  293, 297[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  294, 298[0m:[39m[49m         // Recency: days since most recent affirmed mention. Recent = more relevant.
[0m[49m[39m  295, 299[0m:[39m[49m         IF domain_mentions is not empty:
[0m[49m[39m  296, 300[0m:[39m[49m             features[domain + "_days_since_last"] = days between today and max(encounter_dates)
[0m[49m[39m  297, 301[0m:[39m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  298, 302[0m:[39m[49m             features[domain + "_days_since_last"] = NULL  // explicitly missing, not zero
[0m[49m[39m  299, 303[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  300, 304[0m:[39m[49m         // Negation signal: was this domain explicitly screened negative?
[0m[49m[39m  301, 305[0m:[39m[49m         negated = filter extractions where domain = domain AND assertion = "NEGATED"
[0m[49m[39m  302, 306[0m:[39m[49m         features[domain + "_negated"] = (count of negated > 0)
[0m[49m[39m  303, 307[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  304, 308[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Structured screening features ---
[0m[49m[39m  305, 309[0m:[39m[49m     screening = query screening database for patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  306, 310[0m:[39m[49m     IF screening exists:
[0m[49m[39m  307, 311[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_completed"] = TRUE
[0m[49m[39m  308, 312[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_date"] = screening.date
[0m[49m[39m  309, 313[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_food_score"] = screening.food_insecurity_score
[0m[49m[39m  310, 314[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_housing_score"] = screening.housing_instability_score
[0m[49m[39m  311, 315[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_transport_score"] = screening.transportation_score
[0m[49m[39m  312, 316[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_financial_score"] = screening.financial_strain_score
[0m[49m[39m  313, 317[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_social_score"] = screening.social_isolation_score
[0m[49m[39m  314, 318[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_safety_score"] = screening.safety_score
[0m[49m[39m  315, 319[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  316, 320[0m:[39m[49m         features["screening_completed"] = FALSE
[0m[49m[39m  317, 321[0m:[39m[49m         // All screening scores remain NULL (not zero)
[0m[49m[39m  318, 322[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  319, 323[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Community-level features ---
[0m[49m[39m  320, 324[0m:[39m[49m     address = get most recent address for patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  321, 325[0m:[39m[49m     IF address exists:
[0m[49m[39m  322, 326[0m:[39m[49m         geocode_result = call LocationService.SearchPlaceIndex(Text = address)
[0m[49m[39m  323, 327[0m:[39m[49m         census_tract = lookup_census_tract(geocode_result.coordinates)
[0m[49m[39m  324, 328[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  325, 329[0m:[39m[49m         features["adi_national_rank"] = lookup_adi(census_tract)          // 1-100, higher = more deprived
[0m[49m[39m  326, 330[0m:[39m[49m         features["food_desert_flag"] = lookup_food_desert(census_tract)   // binary
[0m[49m[39m  327, 331[0m:[39m[49m         features["svi_overall"] = lookup_svi(census_tract)                // 0-1, higher = more vulnerable
[0m[49m[39m  328, 332[0m:[39m[49m         features["svi_housing_transport"] = lookup_svi_theme(census_tract, "housing_transport")
[0m[49m[39m  329, 333[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  330, 334[0m:[39m[49m         // No address on file. Community features are NULL.
[0m[49m[39m  331, 335[0m:[39m[49m         features["adi_national_rank"] = NULL
[0m[49m[39m  332, 336[0m:[39m[49m         features["food_desert_flag"] = NULL
[0m[49m[39m  333, 337[0m:[39m[49m         features["svi_overall"] = NULL
[0m[49m[39m  334, 338[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  335, 339[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Derived features ---
[0m[49m[39m  336, 340[0m:[39m[49m     // Total SDOH burden: count of domains with affirmed mentions
[0m[49m[39m  337, 341[0m:[39m[49m     features["sdoh_burden_count"] = count of domains where features[domain + "_present"] = TRUE
[0m[49m[39m  338, 342[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  339, 343[0m:[39m[49m     // Documentation density: total notes in lookback period.
[0m[49m[39m  340, 344[0m:[39m[49m     // Low documentation density means NLP absence is less informative.
[0m[49m[39m  341, 345[0m:[39m[49m     features["note_count_in_window"] = count notes for patient_id in lookback window
[0m[49m[39m  342, 346[0m:[39m[49m     features["sdoh_mention_density"] = total affirmed mentions / features["note_count_in_window"]
[0m[49m[39m  343, 347[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  344, 348[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[39m  345, 349[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  346, 350[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 347     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 3: Clustering.** With the feature matrix assembled, this step applies a clustering algorithm to discover natural groupings of patients by social determinant profile. The choice of algorithm matters: we use Gower distance (which handles mixed binary, categorical, and continuous features natively) with hierarchical agglomerative clustering. This avoids the need to impute missing values or force everything into a numeric space. The optimal number of clusters is determined by a combination of silhouette score (statistical) and clinical interpretability (human judgment). In practice, SDOH phenotyping tends to produce 4-8 meaningful clusters. Fewer than 4 is too coarse to be actionable; more than 8 is too granular for care management teams to operationalize.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Clustering.** With the feature matrix assembled, this step applies a clustering algorithm to discover natural groupings of patients by social determinant profile. The choice of algorithm matters: we use Gower distance (which handles mixed binary, categorical, and continuous features natively) with hierarchical agglomerative clustering using average linkage (UPGMA). Average linkage is valid for non-Euclidean distance matrices like Gower. (Ward's linkage, while popular, requires Euclidean distances and produces unreliable results with Gower.) The optimal number of clusters is determined by a combination of silhouette score (statistical) and clinical interpretability (human judgment). In practice, SDOH phenotyping tends to produce 4-8 meaningful clusters. Fewer than 4 is too coarse to be actionable; more than 8 is too granular for care management teams to operationalize.
[0m[49m[39m  348, 352[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  349, 353[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  350, 354[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION cluster_patients(feature_matrix, min_k = 4, max_k = 8):
[0m[49m[39m  351, 355[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute pairwise Gower distance matrix.
[0m[49m[39m  352, 356[0m:[39m[49m     // Gower distance handles mixed types:
[0m[49m[39m  353, 357[0m:[39m[49m     //   - Binary features: simple matching (0 if same, 1 if different)
[0m[49m[39m  354, 358[0m:[39m[49m     //   - Continuous features: normalized absolute difference
[0m[49m[39m  355, 359[0m:[39m[49m     //   - Missing values: excluded from that pair's distance calculation
[0m[49m[39m  356, 360[0m:[39m[49m     //     (distance computed only over shared non-null features)
[0m[49m[39m  357, 361[0m:[39m[49m     distance_matrix = compute_gower_distance(feature_matrix)
[0m[49m[39m  358, 362[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  359, 363[0m:[39m[49m     // Try each candidate cluster count and evaluate.
[0m[49m[39m  360, 364[0m:[39m[49m     best_k = min_k
[0m[49m[39m  361, 365[0m:[39m[49m     best_score = -1
[0m[49m[39m  362, 366[0m:[39m[49m     results = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  363, 367[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  364, 368[0m:[39m[49m     FOR k in range(min_k, max_k + 1):
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 365     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         // Hierarchical agglomerative clustering with Ward's linkage.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 366     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         // Ward's minimizes within-cluster variance, producing compact clusters.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 367     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         labels = hierarchical_cluster(distance_matrix, method = "ward", n_clusters = k)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Hierarchical agglomerative clustering with average linkage (UPGMA).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Average linkage is valid for non-Euclidean distances like Gower.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Ward's linkage requires Euclidean distances and would produce
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // unreliable results here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         labels = hierarchical_cluster(distance_matrix, method = "average", n_clusters = k)
[0m[49m[39m  368, 374[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  369, 375[0m:[39m[49m         // Silhouette score: how well-separated are the clusters?
[0m[49m[39m  370, 376[0m:[39m[49m         // Range: -1 to 1. Higher is better. Above 0.3 is reasonable for social data.
[0m[49m[39m  371, 377[0m:[39m[49m         silhouette = compute_silhouette(distance_matrix, labels)
[0m[49m[39m  372, 378[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  373, 379[0m:[39m[49m         // Store results for comparison.
[0m[49m[39m  374, 380[0m:[39m[49m         results[k] = { labels: labels, silhouette: silhouette }
[0m[49m[39m  375, 381[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  376, 382[0m:[39m[49m         IF silhouette > best_score:
[0m[49m[39m  377, 383[0m:[39m[49m             best_score = silhouette
[0m[49m[39m  378, 384[0m:[39m[49m             best_k = k
[0m[49m[39m  379, 385[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  380, 386[0m:[39m[49m     // Return the best clustering for clinical review.
[0m[49m[39m  381, 387[0m:[39m[49m     // The final k may be adjusted after clinical validation (Step 4).
[0m[49m[39m  382, 388[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN results[best_k]
[0m[49m[39m  383, 389[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  384, 390[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  385, 391[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Phenotype characterization and validation.** Raw cluster labels (0, 1, 2, ...) are meaningless to care teams. This step characterizes each cluster by its dominant features and assigns a human-readable phenotype name. It also runs the equity audit: checking whether clusters correlate with race/ethnicity in ways that could enable discrimination. The output is a phenotype catalog that care management teams can use to match patients to interventions.
[0m[49m[39m  386, 392[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  387, 393[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  388, 394[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION characterize_phenotypes(feature_matrix, cluster_labels, patient_demographics):
[0m[49m[39m  389, 395[0m:[39m[49m     phenotypes = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  390, 396[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  391, 397[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each cluster_id in unique(cluster_labels):
[0m[49m[39m  392, 398[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_patients = filter feature_matrix where label = cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  393, 399[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_size = count of cluster_patients
[0m[49m[39m  394, 400[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  395, 401[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute feature prevalence within this cluster.
[0m[49m[39m  396, 402[0m:[39m[49m         // Which SDOH domains are most common in this group?
[0m[49m[39m  397, 403[0m:[39m[49m         profile = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  398, 404[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each domain in SDOH_DOMAINS:
[0m[49m[39m  399, 405[0m:[39m[49m             prevalence = mean of cluster_patients[domain + "_present"]
[0m[49m[39m  400, 406[0m:[39m[49m             profile[domain] = prevalence
[0m[49m[39m  401, 407[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  402, 408[0m:[39m[49m         // Identify dominant features (prevalence > 50% in cluster).
[0m[49m[39m  403, 409[0m:[39m[49m         dominant_domains = filter profile where prevalence > 0.5
[0m[49m[39m  404, 410[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  405, 411[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute community indicator averages.
[0m[49m[39m  406, 412[0m:[39m[49m         avg_adi = mean of cluster_patients["adi_national_rank"]
[0m[49m[39m  407, 413[0m:[39m[49m         avg_svi = mean of cluster_patients["svi_overall"]
[0m[49m[39m  408, 414[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  409, 415[0m:[39m[49m         // --- Equity audit ---
[0m[49m[39m  410, 416[0m:[39m[49m         // Check demographic composition of this cluster.
[0m[49m[39m  411, 417[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_demographics = filter patient_demographics where label = cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  412, 418[0m:[39m[49m         race_distribution = compute distribution of cluster_demographics.race
[0m[49m[39m  413, 419[0m:[39m[49m         // Flag if any racial group is overrepresented by more than 2x
[0m[49m[39m  414, 420[0m:[39m[49m         // compared to the overall population.
[0m[49m[39m  415, 421[0m:[39m[49m         equity_flags = check_overrepresentation(race_distribution, overall_distribution, threshold = 2.0)
[0m[49m[39m  416, 422[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  417, 423[0m:[39m[49m         phenotype = {
[0m[49m[39m  418, 424[0m:[39m[49m             cluster_id:       cluster_id,
[0m[49m[39m  419, 425[0m:[39m[49m             size:             cluster_size,
[0m[49m[39m  420, 426[0m:[39m[49m             dominant_domains: dominant_domains,
[0m[49m[39m  421, 427[0m:[39m[49m             avg_adi:          avg_adi,
[0m[49m[39m  422, 428[0m:[39m[49m             avg_svi:          avg_svi,
[0m[49m[39m  423, 429[0m:[39m[49m             equity_flags:     equity_flags,
[0m[49m[39m  424, 430[0m:[39m[49m             // Human-readable name assigned after clinical review.
[0m[49m[39m  425, 431[0m:[39m[49m             // Examples: "Housing + Food Insecurity", "Transportation Barrier Only",
[0m[49m[39m  426, 432[0m:[39m[49m             //           "Multi-Domain Social Complexity", "Low Documentation / Unknown"
[0m[49m[39m  427, 433[0m:[39m[49m             name:             NULL  // assigned by clinical team in validation
[0m[49m[39m  428, 434[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  429, 435[0m:[39m[49m         append phenotype to phenotypes
[0m[49m[39m  430, 436[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  431, 437[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN phenotypes
[0m[49m[39m  432, 438[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  433, 439[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  434, 440[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Store phenotype assignments.** Write each patient's phenotype assignment to the real-time lookup store. Include the assignment date, confidence (membership probability if using soft clustering), and a staleness indicator. Phenotypes decay: a patient's social circumstances change, and an assignment from 18 months ago may no longer reflect reality. Downstream systems should check the assignment date and trigger re-evaluation if it's stale.
[0m[49m[39m  435, 441[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S3 (MEDIUM). Add note that feature_snapshot is derived PHI subject to the same retention and access controls as source data. Consider recommending an S3 URI reference in DynamoDB rather than the full snapshot, to reduce PHI surface in the real-time lookup store. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S4 (MEDIUM). Add requirement for application-level audit logging at the care management integration point: each phenotype lookup should log requesting user/system, patient_id, timestamp, and phenotype returned (HIPAA accounting-of-disclosures control). -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  436, 446[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  437, 447[0m:[39m[49m STALENESS_THRESHOLD_DAYS = 180  // re-evaluate phenotype if older than 6 months
[0m[49m[39m  438, 448[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  439, 449[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_phenotype_assignment(patient_id, phenotype, confidence, feature_snapshot):
[0m[49m[39m  440, 450[0m:[39m[49m     write to DynamoDB table "patient-phenotypes":
[0m[49m[39m  441, 451[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id       = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  442, 452[0m:[39m[49m         phenotype_id     = phenotype.cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  443, 453[0m:[39m[49m         phenotype_name   = phenotype.name
[0m[49m[39m  444, 454[0m:[39m[49m         confidence       = confidence                    // membership probability (0-1)
[0m[49m[39m  445, 455[0m:[39m[49m         assigned_date    = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  446, 456[0m:[39m[49m         dominant_domains = phenotype.dominant_domains    // for quick reference without full lookup
[0m[49m[39m  447, 457[0m:[39m[49m         feature_snapshot = feature_snapshot              // the features at time of assignment
[0m[49m[39m  448, 458[0m:[39m[49m         stale_after      = today + STALENESS_THRESHOLD_DAYS
[0m[49m[39m  449, 459[0m:[39m[49m         version          = clustering model version     // track which model produced this
[0m[49m[39m  450, 460[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  451, 461[0m:[39m[49m 
